Kazakhstan's GDP up 2.1 Percent
Kazakhstan's half-year gross domestic product (GDP) rose 2.1 percent
and industrial output was up 1 percent, compared with the same period
of last year, the Kazak Telegraph Agency reported Tuesday.
During the first half of this year, national revenues were about 1.7
billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 84 percent of the planned target;
expenditures were 2.1 billion dollars, or 81.4 percent of the plan,
with a deficit of 380 million dollars, according to government figures
released Tuesday.
Prime Minister Nurlan Utebovich Balgimbaev attributed the stable growth
of the economy to the support of the government and increased bank
loans.
Balgimbaev said the government is drawing an investment plan to
stabilize the economy and stimulate production.
